1
00:02:39,920 --> 00:02:41,273
There you are!

2
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,390
How was your day?
Any progress in saving the world?

3
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:47,193
I'm working on it.

4
00:02:49,160 --> 00:02:51,037
You changed your mind about tonight?

5
00:02:51,320 --> 00:02:53,959
Not really. Told you
I didn't want to miss it.

6
00:02:54,520 --> 00:02:56,431
What happened with that dinner
with the London people?

7
00:02:56,720 --> 00:02:59,188
-You made it sound so unavoidable.
-It was.

8
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:01,232
Fortunately, they missed their plane.

9
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:06,073
Here's to...

10
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:08,032
...stolen moments.

11
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:17,476
You look so handsome,
I better see if I can catch up.

12
00:03:39,400 --> 00:03:40,196
Nobody home?

13
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:44,110
I left some Security Council
transcripts out, but everybody's gone.

14
00:03:44,880 --> 00:03:46,757
Anything earth-shattering?

15
00:03:47,080 --> 00:03:50,675
No, it's just important enough
not to be left out.

16
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:53,918
You look incredible.

17
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:56,678
Yeah, but we have to hurry.

18
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:13,308
I prefer this one.

19
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:18,115
Right.

20
00:04:44,920 --> 00:04:46,717
Can I have a picture, please?

21
00:04:46,920 --> 00:04:48,672
This way. This way, please.

22
00:04:57,960 --> 00:05:00,633
There's Andrew. Good to see him.
Robynn, hi.

23
00:05:00,920 --> 00:05:02,433
Steven, how are you?

24
00:05:02,720 --> 00:05:04,153
Nice to see you.
Emily, you look wonderful.

25
00:05:04,440 --> 00:05:05,668
Keep up the good work.

26
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:08,878
That's Steven Taylor
and his wife, Emily.

27
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:10,755
Well, at last!

28
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:12,632
The beautiful people have arrived.

29
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:14,074
Fantastic dress!

30
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:15,676
Thank you.

31
00:05:16,440 --> 00:05:18,795
I didn't expect to see you tonight,
with Greenspan and all.

32
00:05:19,040 --> 00:05:19,916
Why's that?

33
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:21,957
I thought you'd be
up to your ass in alligators.

34
00:05:22,200 --> 00:05:25,476
Rumors of my death have been
greatly exaggerated.

35
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:27,991
All I need is her phone number.

36
00:05:28,240 --> 00:05:30,470
Absolutely.
I must see about something.

37
00:05:30,720 --> 00:05:32,517
Lovely!
Thank you, darling.

38
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:36,437
The temple's hieroglyphics
are supplications...

39
00:05:36,680 --> 00:05:37,829
...to the gods of fertility.

40
00:05:38,120 --> 00:05:39,997
I do believe I know his work.

41
00:05:40,240 --> 00:05:43,596
Perhaps we could come along
to your studio one day.

42
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:12,349
You said he wasn't coming.

43
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:15,034
He changed his mind.
I tried to call you.

44
00:06:15,640 --> 00:06:17,278
What are we going to do?

45
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:20,869
Nothing. Just relax.

46
00:06:21,680 --> 00:06:24,148
-He doesn't know who I am, right?
-No.

47
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:27,478
You're a peach.

48
00:06:28,480 --> 00:06:30,072
Lunch tomorrow?

49
00:06:30,760 --> 00:06:32,273
And tomorrow...

50
00:06:32,480 --> 00:06:33,913
...and tomorrow.

51
00:06:34,560 --> 00:06:38,155
I leave you alone for 30 seconds
and you elope with a younger man.

52
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,278
Steven, I'd like to
introduce you to David Shaw.

53
00:06:41,520 --> 00:06:42,919
Pleasure! Nice to meet you.

54
00:06:43,160 --> 00:06:44,195
David is a painter.

55
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:47,677
I saw some of his pieces downtown.
I thought they were amazing.

56
00:06:47,960 --> 00:06:50,474
What brings you uptown to our
little inbred soirée?

57
00:06:50,960 --> 00:06:54,270
Actually, Emily was kind enough
to wrangle me an invite.

58
00:06:54,520 --> 00:06:55,748
Me too.

59
00:06:57,880 --> 00:06:59,757
So tell me about your work...

60
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,029
...David?

61
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,550
A couple small galleries
carry me when there's space.

62
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:06,798
-You studied formally?
-Berkeley, Cal Arts.

63
00:07:07,040 --> 00:07:09,508
Almost formally graduated too.

64
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:12,352
Too much study pollutes the soul.

65
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:14,596
-And he's good?
-He's wonderful.

66
00:07:14,840 --> 00:07:18,037
I'd love to see your pieces.
Maybe we can arrange a time.

67
00:07:18,280 --> 00:07:21,113
-Whenever you want.
-Emily has your number?

68
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:25,637
No. The gallery can get ahold of me.
You know which one?

69
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:28,119
Yes.

70
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:30,433
If you're as good as she says...

71
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:33,274
...l'll pass the word on
to my acquisitive friends.

72
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,353
Thanks. That's very generous.

73
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:38,069
Nice to meet you.

74
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:39,749
You too.

75
00:07:39,960 --> 00:07:41,473
Pleasure to see you.

76
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:04,632
We cannot be held accountable...

77
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:08,037
...for the actions of others
that require us to defend ourselves.

78
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:13,994
Madame Ambassador.

79
00:08:14,800 --> 00:08:18,759
It's the same speech he gave in
Geneva 3 months ago, word for word.

80
00:08:24,280 --> 00:08:25,633
Showoff.

81
00:08:26,520 --> 00:08:28,875
-Good morning, how are you?
-Fine, thank you.

82
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:31,754
Steven, spreads are blowing out.

83
00:08:32,040 --> 00:08:35,157
The way things look in Europe,
it could turn into a bloodbath.

84
00:08:35,440 --> 00:08:39,035
-So what are we talking?
-At least 1 50 basis points.

85
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:40,753
The Bundesbank will have to tag along.

86
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:43,719
Your yen and mark positions
will get hammered.

87
00:08:44,240 --> 00:08:45,593
So what's our exposure?

88
00:08:45,840 --> 00:08:47,592
Based on my preliminary trend model?

89
00:08:47,840 --> 00:08:49,159
Yes. No frills.

90
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:51,152
Think Chernobyl.

91
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,070
Greenpoint, next stop.

92
00:09:27,760 --> 00:09:28,829
What you got there?

93
00:09:29,080 --> 00:09:30,672
It's a little surprise.

94
00:09:31,160 --> 00:09:32,673
Come on up.

95
00:09:37,560 --> 00:09:39,073
Here's your fortune.

96
00:09:40,360 --> 00:09:44,433
"You have a deep interest
in all that is artistic."

97
00:09:45,320 --> 00:09:46,514
It's true.

98
00:09:49,040 --> 00:09:50,871
You didn't have to get this for me.

99
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:54,708
You need a little civilizing.

100
00:09:57,760 --> 00:09:59,273
What do you need?

101
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:05,079
What do you need?

102
00:10:11,960 --> 00:10:14,872
You know, we could be in Belize
this time tomorrow.

103
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:16,999
Belize.

104
00:10:17,440 --> 00:10:19,192
You ever been there?

105
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:22,515
You'd think you'd died
and went to heaven.

106
00:10:22,760 --> 00:10:24,671
But I already think that.

107
00:10:35,840 --> 00:10:37,876
You look so pretty today.

108
00:11:47,800 --> 00:11:51,236
Hey, it's David. Leave one.
I'll get back to you.

109
00:11:52,560 --> 00:11:55,916
David, hi. It's Steven Taylor.
I'm finishing a little early today.

110
00:11:56,160 --> 00:11:58,993
I thought I might come by
and check out your work.

111
00:11:59,240 --> 00:12:01,151
Say about six.

112
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:06,710
If that flies with you, call me
at my office here at 5-4-4-...

113
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:08,678
... 1-8-1-7.

114
00:12:10,120 --> 00:12:12,236
I look forward to seeing you.

115
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:16,951
What are you going to do?

116
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:21,476
I guess I'll call him.

117
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:24,949
Be kind of weird if I didn't,
wouldn't it?

118
00:12:25,560 --> 00:12:27,869
You're playing with fire, David.

119
00:12:30,480 --> 00:12:33,677
If you're so upset about it,
why'd you give him my number?

120
00:12:34,760 --> 00:12:36,512
I didn't.

121
00:12:56,120 --> 00:12:57,473
Mr. Taylor?

122
00:12:58,320 --> 00:12:59,833
Hi. Here, sit down.

123
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:03,950
That was stupid. Sorry about that.

124
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:08,998
Thanks very much.

125
00:13:09,840 --> 00:13:10,670
Drink?

126
00:13:11,320 --> 00:13:12,878
No, I'm okay.

127
00:13:13,120 --> 00:13:14,951
Unless you want another one.

128
00:13:15,280 --> 00:13:17,748
I just had us meet here
because my place is hard to find.

129
00:13:18,040 --> 00:13:19,792
Like an illegal loft space?

130
00:13:21,240 --> 00:13:22,639
That's one way to put it.

131
00:13:23,520 --> 00:13:26,671
I feel like I'm knee-deep
in bohemian cachet.

132
00:13:26,960 --> 00:13:28,234
Lead on.

133
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:40,993
-How's Emily?
-She's fine, thank you.

134
00:13:42,440 --> 00:13:44,351
Well, be sure and say "hi."

135
00:13:44,600 --> 00:13:45,919
I will.

136
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:50,468
One more.
One more floor.

137
00:13:50,760 --> 00:13:53,228
Building's over 100 years old now.

138
00:13:58,160 --> 00:13:59,673
Watch your step.

139
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:19,518
I can certainly see
what Emily was drawn to.

140
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:21,274
Yeah? What's that?

141
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:23,592
Your work. It's...

142
00:14:23,920 --> 00:14:25,797
...very trashy...

143
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:27,310
...but potent.

144
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:28,635
Trashy?

145
00:14:29,040 --> 00:14:30,473
Is that what she said?

146
00:14:35,320 --> 00:14:36,799
Your anger...

147
00:14:37,680 --> 00:14:39,079
...it's very controlled.

148
00:14:39,760 --> 00:14:41,318
You think I'm angry?

149
00:14:42,720 --> 00:14:44,597
The anger in your work.

150
00:14:45,200 --> 00:14:47,350
The color of despair.

151
00:14:48,440 --> 00:14:50,271
Wonder where that comes from.

152
00:14:51,440 --> 00:14:52,873
I don't know.

153
00:14:53,480 --> 00:14:55,038
Inside, I guess.

154
00:14:55,320 --> 00:14:56,309
Inside...

155
00:14:56,560 --> 00:14:57,675
...indeed.

156
00:15:00,880 --> 00:15:03,189
Nowhere to sit but the goddamned bed.

157
00:15:12,720 --> 00:15:14,597
You know, I envy you.

158
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:16,308
You envy me?

159
00:15:16,560 --> 00:15:17,913
You should be...

160
00:15:18,200 --> 00:15:20,668
...flattered.
I'm not prone to envy.

161
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:23,639
It's a pathetic emotion.

162
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,195
Sneaks up on you like cancer.

163
00:15:27,440 --> 00:15:29,032
I've got it and you know why.

164
00:15:31,680 --> 00:15:32,396
No.

165
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:34,278
Oh, of course you do.

166
00:15:35,440 --> 00:15:39,911
One of life's legitimately
sublime experiences. It's so...

167
00:15:40,800 --> 00:15:42,358
...utterly complete.

168
00:15:42,640 --> 00:15:43,470
What?

169
00:15:44,440 --> 00:15:46,271
Fucking my wife.

170
00:15:49,200 --> 00:15:50,872
Mr. Taylor, I don't know...

171
00:15:51,120 --> 00:15:54,032
I think it's about time
you called me Steven.

172
00:15:57,520 --> 00:15:59,078
We're in love, sir.

173
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:02,273
That's it?

174
00:16:03,320 --> 00:16:04,469
That's it?

175
00:16:05,360 --> 00:16:08,636
You steal the crown jewel
of a man's soul...

176
00:16:08,920 --> 00:16:12,993
...and your only excuse is some
candy-ass Hallmark card sentiment?

177
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:15,350
Even if it was true,
that's not good enough!

178
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:17,679
If what were true?

179
00:16:17,920 --> 00:16:19,239
She is in love.

180
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:20,475
You, buddy...

181
00:16:20,760 --> 00:16:21,988
...you're in business.

182
00:16:22,240 --> 00:16:23,389
What the hell are you saying?

183
00:16:23,640 --> 00:16:26,712
I'm saying you did not meet
my wife by chance.

184
00:16:27,600 --> 00:16:30,194
I'm saying
you didn't study at Berkeley.

185
00:16:33,040 --> 00:16:37,477
I'm saying you learned to paint while
doing 3 to 6 in Soledad Prison...

186
00:16:37,720 --> 00:16:41,872
...for relieving a widow
in San Francisco of her life savings.

187
00:16:42,160 --> 00:16:43,354
Your second conviction...

188
00:16:44,080 --> 00:16:45,957
...if I'm not mistaken.

189
00:16:48,280 --> 00:16:51,829
Your real name is Winston Lagrange,
which I rather like.

190
00:16:52,120 --> 00:16:55,078
Born to pure trailer trash
in Barstow, California.

191
00:16:55,320 --> 00:16:57,231
Ward of the courts
since the age of ten.

192
00:16:57,480 --> 00:17:01,109
You went from pickpocket to car thief
to con man till you found out...

193
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:04,079
...that you had a way
with the softer sex.

194
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:07,872
No doubt looking for that mother
you can barely remember.

195
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:12,036
A life made up completely
of depressing little scams...

196
00:17:12,280 --> 00:17:13,156
...until now.

197
00:17:13,400 --> 00:17:14,879
Where'd you get all that?

198
00:17:15,120 --> 00:17:18,078
All that is for sale.
The hell of it is, you're not...

199
00:17:18,360 --> 00:17:20,476
...half-bad with a brush.

200
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:22,718
Called rehabilitation.

201
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:25,429
It's called a con.
My wife's the grand prize.

202
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:28,234
But you set your sights
too high this time.

203
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:30,438
She loves me.

204
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:32,472
She loves David Shaw,
your invention.

205
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:36,309
But you've made
a fundamental miscalculation.

206
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:37,715
Play it out.

207
00:17:38,080 --> 00:17:39,513
Love conquers all.

208
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:42,394
Emily divorces me.
She marries you.

209
00:17:44,360 --> 00:17:48,478
Given your history, her advisors
are going to insist upon a prenup.

210
00:17:49,480 --> 00:17:51,038
You might storm the castle...

211
00:17:51,280 --> 00:17:54,158
...but you ain't getting the keys
to the treasure room, ever.

212
00:17:54,440 --> 00:17:55,714
I don't care about that.

213
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:59,470
The swindler doesn't care about a
trust fund that can buy Barstow?

214
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:01,318
Why don't you cut the shit!

215
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:04,472
You care, or we would not be having
this conversation!

216
00:18:05,440 --> 00:18:09,592
The only thing that stops you from
bolting now is bad genes and greed.

217
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:14,554
Now what?

218
00:18:15,400 --> 00:18:16,799
Choices.

219
00:18:17,480 --> 00:18:20,836
I can tell Emily who you are,
and life will imitate art.

220
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:22,871
You become a starving painter,
game over.

221
00:18:24,520 --> 00:18:25,589
Or?

222
00:18:26,560 --> 00:18:28,437
Or you can cash out.

223
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:30,519
Cash out?

224
00:18:30,800 --> 00:18:32,233
Half a million dollars.

225
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:34,479
Tax-free.

226
00:18:38,040 --> 00:18:40,270
Just for walking away from her?

227
00:18:40,840 --> 00:18:43,274
I said tax-free.
I didn't say free.

228
00:18:45,680 --> 00:18:47,511
What's 500 grand for?

229
00:18:49,160 --> 00:18:51,151
Killing my wife.

230
00:18:59,440 --> 00:19:00,555
Emily?

231
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:03,594
Imagine my embarrassment
if they're not the same.

232
00:19:03,840 --> 00:19:05,796
$100,000 now...

233
00:19:06,080 --> 00:19:08,913
...$400,000 after, cash-and-carry.

234
00:19:15,560 --> 00:19:17,232
You're out of your mind.

235
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:19,518
Not really.

236
00:19:21,080 --> 00:19:21,956
Why?

237
00:19:22,800 --> 00:19:27,271
I appreciate your curiosity,
but my agenda doesn't concern you.

238
00:19:29,440 --> 00:19:32,238
I'll go straight to Emily
and tell her all this.

239
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:36,551
That would be my word against yours...

240
00:19:36,840 --> 00:19:37,875
...Winston.

241
00:19:38,200 --> 00:19:40,031
And what if I call the cops?

242
00:19:43,040 --> 00:19:46,669
Have you ever been
to Boca Raton, Florida?

243
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:53,559
A lady there was carrying on
with a younger man.

244
00:19:53,840 --> 00:19:57,549
He was a hell of a tennis player.
When the affair ended...

245
00:19:58,160 --> 00:19:59,479
...he disappeared...

246
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:02,479
...along with the lady's bearer bonds.

247
00:20:04,600 --> 00:20:06,113
You sure you've never been there?

248
00:20:07,480 --> 00:20:09,277
Not that I recall.

249
00:20:10,240 --> 00:20:14,472
An acquaintance of mine has
a photograph of the suspect.

250
00:20:15,880 --> 00:20:17,996
All they need is a name...

251
00:20:19,480 --> 00:20:21,471
...as in, strike three.

252
00:20:22,880 --> 00:20:24,074
1 5 years.

253
00:20:24,480 --> 00:20:26,038
No parole.

254
00:20:27,800 --> 00:20:32,112
You think you got a box big enough
to hold $100,000 in cash?

255
00:20:34,560 --> 00:20:37,836
Come by the apartment
around 1 2 o'clock tomorrow.

256
00:20:38,560 --> 00:20:41,438
Unless you have
a previous luncheon engagement.

257
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:46,315
I assume you know where I live.

258
00:21:39,040 --> 00:21:40,314
I'm your best friend!

259
00:21:40,520 --> 00:21:43,318
Half the year goes by
and you don't say one thing?

260
00:21:43,560 --> 00:21:45,755
Do you love him?
Will you leave Steven?

261
00:21:46,240 --> 00:21:47,309
Talk to me.

262
00:21:47,560 --> 00:21:49,516
I will if you shut up for one second.

263
00:21:50,040 --> 00:21:51,678
I'm waiting.

264
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:55,350
I didn't tell you
because you adore Steven.

265
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:57,477
You cried at our wedding,
for God's sake.

266
00:21:57,800 --> 00:22:00,473
-I cry at every wedding.
-No, you don't.

267
00:22:01,480 --> 00:22:03,516
You like the idea of us.

268
00:22:03,720 --> 00:22:05,392
Everybody does.

269
00:22:05,600 --> 00:22:07,989
But you have no idea who he is.

270
00:22:08,360 --> 00:22:10,396
-I know Steven.
-No, you don't.

271
00:22:11,480 --> 00:22:16,156
You don't know that everything
always has to be on his terms.

272
00:22:16,520 --> 00:22:20,274
You don't know that he has
no real interest in who I am.

273
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:28,435
What are you going to do?

274
00:22:28,640 --> 00:22:30,073
I don't know.

275
00:22:30,600 --> 00:22:33,797
I'm going to figure out a way
to tell him. He deserves that.

276
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:35,877
What makes you think he doesn't know?

277
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:37,798
Because there's no way.

278
00:22:38,080 --> 00:22:41,675
I mean, he knows that
something's not right but...

279
00:22:43,720 --> 00:22:45,756
Does David have a last name?

280
00:22:46,680 --> 00:22:48,352
Shaw. David Shaw.

281
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:51,030
And he knows about your family?

282
00:22:51,320 --> 00:22:52,878
What do you mean?

283
00:22:53,920 --> 00:22:54,830
What do you think I mean?

284
00:22:55,120 --> 00:22:58,032
We don't talk about that kind of stuff.

285
00:22:58,320 --> 00:23:00,038
In six months,
you never mentioned money?

286
00:23:00,320 --> 00:23:01,355
No!

287
00:23:01,640 --> 00:23:03,437
Believe me, okay?

288
00:23:03,720 --> 00:23:08,111
David has absolutely no interest
in anything other than painting...

289
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:10,553
...and me.

290
00:23:10,840 --> 00:23:12,273
And you.

291
00:23:13,680 --> 00:23:15,636
Is that why you're not wearing
your wedding ring?

292
00:23:20,440 --> 00:23:21,793
Oh, my God!

293
00:23:22,960 --> 00:23:23,870
What?

294
00:23:24,520 --> 00:23:26,272
I left it at David's.

295
00:23:36,080 --> 00:23:37,479
Working late?

296
00:23:38,840 --> 00:23:40,637
No, I was having a drink with Raquel.

297
00:23:40,920 --> 00:23:44,196
And how is the Castilian femme fatale?

298
00:23:46,800 --> 00:23:49,951
By the way, I saw your friend
David this evening.

299
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:51,469
Really?

300
00:23:51,720 --> 00:23:54,917
He honored me with a visit
at his industrial hideaway.

301
00:23:55,120 --> 00:23:56,030
You're kidding.

302
00:23:56,680 --> 00:23:58,750
And where's that?

303
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:00,712
Greenpoint, Brooklyn.

304
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:02,479
How'd you get his number?

305
00:24:02,760 --> 00:24:06,230
I called some of those
obscure galleries you prowl...

306
00:24:06,520 --> 00:24:08,317
...dropped your name.

307
00:24:08,920 --> 00:24:09,796
You're right.

308
00:24:10,160 --> 00:24:11,912
He's very talented.

309
00:24:14,480 --> 00:24:15,799
Did you buy anything?

310
00:24:16,080 --> 00:24:17,798
I made him an offer.

311
00:24:23,760 --> 00:24:24,875
And?

312
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:28,030
And he's chewing on it.

313
00:24:46,240 --> 00:24:47,753
Good morning.

314
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:07,870
-Hi, it's me.
-Hey, how you doing?

315
00:25:08,320 --> 00:25:10,276
-I left my wedding ring.
-I know.

316
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:12,471
I put it away before he got here.

317
00:25:12,760 --> 00:25:14,273
Thank God!

318
00:25:16,520 --> 00:25:18,033
What did you guys talk about?

319
00:25:19,960 --> 00:25:23,555
He wasn't here that long,
so just the work.

320
00:25:23,840 --> 00:25:25,159
He didn't have a clue.

321
00:25:26,480 --> 00:25:29,313
He said that he made you an offer.

322
00:25:29,640 --> 00:25:30,914
Matter of fact, he did.

323
00:25:31,200 --> 00:25:32,235
What piece?

324
00:25:32,480 --> 00:25:34,755
It's one you haven't seen.

325
00:25:35,520 --> 00:25:36,873
I thought I'd seen all of them.

326
00:25:37,160 --> 00:25:38,752
Well, almost.

327
00:25:39,640 --> 00:25:43,235
Listen, turns out I got to take
a rain check on lunch today.

328
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:46,318
-Why? What's wrong?
-Nothing, nothing.

329
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:49,074
Some people want to see my sketches...

330
00:25:49,360 --> 00:25:50,918
...and it'd be a good commission.

331
00:25:51,720 --> 00:25:52,948
You sound funny.

332
00:25:53,240 --> 00:25:54,389
Do I?

333
00:25:54,680 --> 00:25:55,749
Yeah.

334
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:58,795
I guess it's called
being broke, sweetheart.

335
00:26:00,840 --> 00:26:02,273
Tomorrow, then.

336
00:26:02,920 --> 00:26:04,512
Reservation for two.

337
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:06,711
Quiet table, in back.

338
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:08,319
Very quiet.

339
00:26:10,720 --> 00:26:11,914
You know I love you.

340
00:26:12,320 --> 00:26:13,673
I know.

341
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:15,035
Bye.

342
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:01,518
-Is that by...?
-Yeah.

343
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:05,992
People with money
always go for the same things.

344
00:27:06,880 --> 00:27:08,552
And what are those?

345
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:12,557
Anything, everything,
as long as it's recognizable.

346
00:27:13,360 --> 00:27:16,796
Don't worry. None of this
would've been yours anyway.

347
00:27:17,080 --> 00:27:19,992
Everything you see here, it's mine.

348
00:27:20,280 --> 00:27:22,874
Why don't you drop that
there and come here.

349
00:27:28,600 --> 00:27:29,953
That's nice.

350
00:27:34,840 --> 00:27:37,479
There was a robbery
in the building last year.

351
00:27:37,760 --> 00:27:39,751
Probable means of entrance...

352
00:27:40,040 --> 00:27:41,917
...was this driveway gate.

353
00:27:42,200 --> 00:27:45,829
That granite façade creates a blind
spot on the surveillance cameras.

354
00:27:46,120 --> 00:27:47,951
It was never corrected,
for aesthetic reasons.

355
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:49,389
How do you know that?

356
00:27:49,680 --> 00:27:51,318
I'm on the board.

357
00:27:56,320 --> 00:27:58,709
You enter as I leave at 8 p.m.

358
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:01,958
I won't pull out of the driveway
till it's clear.

359
00:28:02,200 --> 00:28:04,111
The gate takes 5 seconds to close.

360
00:28:04,320 --> 00:28:07,039
Hug the right side of the wall
as I drive by.

361
00:28:07,280 --> 00:28:10,511
Then you enter the stairs
by the service elevator.

362
00:28:10,760 --> 00:28:14,992
The key to the front door also works
here for the service entrance.

363
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,878
I'm going to take the key from
Emily's purse before I leave...

364
00:28:26,120 --> 00:28:27,678
...and I'll put it in this...

365
00:28:27,920 --> 00:28:30,992
...and hide it here,
right behind the pipe.

366
00:28:32,720 --> 00:28:35,598
-Where're you going to be?
-At my regular card game.

367
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:37,274
Why don't you leave me your key?

368
00:28:37,560 --> 00:28:40,028
My key implicates me.
Her key implicates no one.

369
00:28:40,280 --> 00:28:42,077
It could've been lost or stolen.

370
00:28:42,320 --> 00:28:45,232
In any case, she won't
be around to explain.

371
00:28:45,520 --> 00:28:46,919
Why not make a copy of the key?

372
00:28:47,200 --> 00:28:50,237
It's two loose ends,
the key and the locksmith.

373
00:28:51,800 --> 00:28:56,078
This door is always bolted. She
won't notice, even if she checks it.

374
00:28:56,360 --> 00:28:58,590
You'll be in the stairwell at 9:30.

375
00:28:58,880 --> 00:29:01,758
By that time, Emily
will be taking her bath.

376
00:29:02,040 --> 00:29:03,519
She will? How do you know?

377
00:29:03,800 --> 00:29:07,156
Because that's what she does
on nights that I play cards.

378
00:29:08,160 --> 00:29:09,673
Why not do it in the tub?

379
00:29:10,680 --> 00:29:13,194
Because that'll look like
cold-blooded murder.

380
00:29:13,440 --> 00:29:16,671
It has to appear that
she surprised the intruder.

381
00:29:16,920 --> 00:29:18,114
All right?

382
00:29:19,960 --> 00:29:21,871
This is a separate telephone line.

383
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:25,596
Exactly 10 p.m., I will call here.

384
00:29:25,880 --> 00:29:28,110
Emily will answer the phone.

385
00:29:29,200 --> 00:29:30,997
You will enter.

386
00:29:31,680 --> 00:29:34,797
A tragic confrontation will ensue.

387
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:37,632
It should appear to be...

388
00:29:37,920 --> 00:29:39,319
...stupid...

389
00:29:39,800 --> 00:29:41,677
...and spur-of-the-moment.

390
00:29:42,680 --> 00:29:46,992
I've always thought "bludgeon"
has a spur-of-the-moment sound.

391
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:48,554
Maybe you could use one of these.

392
00:29:50,960 --> 00:29:53,520
Rifle the jewelry in the bedroom.

393
00:29:53,800 --> 00:29:57,110
Disable the service entrance lock.
Make it look like it was jimmied.

394
00:29:57,400 --> 00:30:00,870
Put the key back under the pipe,
then leave the way you came in.

395
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:04,036
And what happens
if the plan goes to hell?

396
00:30:05,360 --> 00:30:06,713
It won't.

397
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:25,718
So when is this card game of yours?

398
00:30:25,960 --> 00:30:27,439
-Tomorrow night.
-Tomorrow?

399
00:30:27,800 --> 00:30:29,119
No fucking way!

400
00:30:29,400 --> 00:30:32,358
A man with your résumé should
come up with an alibi in no time.

401
00:30:32,640 --> 00:30:34,392
100 thousand.

402
00:30:37,280 --> 00:30:39,032
A man with my résumé should
take the money and run.

403
00:30:39,320 --> 00:30:41,754
Bet you 400 thousand more you don't.

404
00:31:27,800 --> 00:31:28,676
Yes, I understand that.

405
00:31:28,960 --> 00:31:31,030
But if we can't get numbers
on refugee density...

406
00:31:31,320 --> 00:31:33,709
...then we can't position
the resources to deal with it.

407
00:31:34,200 --> 00:31:37,795
I'll tell her to expect it
later today. Thank you.

408
00:32:02,440 --> 00:32:04,590
That's not happiness to see me, is it?

409
00:32:05,600 --> 00:32:06,919
Try surprise.

410
00:32:07,200 --> 00:32:08,952
I had a hole in my schedule...

411
00:32:09,160 --> 00:32:12,596
...and I thought lunch with my
beautiful wife would be indicated.

412
00:32:13,440 --> 00:32:14,873
But I guess you have other plans.

413
00:32:15,120 --> 00:32:17,156
-What makes you say that?
-You seem in such a hurry.

414
00:32:17,440 --> 00:32:18,589
It's just errands.

415
00:32:18,880 --> 00:32:20,950
Like shopping for a new wedding ring.

416
00:32:21,240 --> 00:32:23,231
One of the settings felt loose...

417
00:32:23,520 --> 00:32:25,829
...so I took it in.
It'll be ready tomorrow.

418
00:32:26,200 --> 00:32:28,031
And what if there were no tomorrow?

419
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:30,154
What does that mean?

420
00:32:30,560 --> 00:32:33,757
Wouldn't you regret not having
one last lunch with your husband?

421
00:32:34,520 --> 00:32:35,873
Of course.

422
00:33:06,800 --> 00:33:09,837
-Enjoy your meal.
-Thank you very much.

423
00:33:21,720 --> 00:33:24,439
I must reply to Francesca about
this weekend. Want to do it?

424
00:33:25,080 --> 00:33:26,672
All right, we'll go out...

425
00:33:28,280 --> 00:33:31,317
I got to break this up.
Excuse me one minute.

426
00:34:30,720 --> 00:34:34,156
Hey, it's David. Leave one.
I'll get back to you.

427
00:34:35,120 --> 00:34:36,109
David?

428
00:34:38,520 --> 00:34:40,317
He was waiting for me...

429
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:41,390
...to take me to lunch.

430
00:34:41,640 --> 00:34:43,551
There was nothing I could do.

431
00:34:49,360 --> 00:34:51,920
I can't do this anymore.
I've got to tell him tonight.

432
00:34:53,600 --> 00:34:54,749
Hi, I'm here.

433
00:34:56,600 --> 00:34:57,715
I'm really sorry.

434
00:34:58,720 --> 00:34:59,550
It's okay.

435
00:34:59,800 --> 00:35:02,678
He's never done that before.
Something's wrong. He knows.

436
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:04,353
No, he doesn't.

437
00:35:04,640 --> 00:35:06,392
Don't let your mind
get away from you.

438
00:35:08,280 --> 00:35:09,998
I cannot live like this anymore.

439
00:35:10,240 --> 00:35:13,152
It's not fair to him.
I've got to tell him.

440
00:35:13,600 --> 00:35:15,431
Tell him what, exactly?

441
00:35:15,720 --> 00:35:17,438
Tell him everything, tonight.

442
00:35:19,760 --> 00:35:21,990
We've waited this long.
Hold off another day...

443
00:35:22,360 --> 00:35:24,476
...so we can figure it out together.

444
00:35:24,880 --> 00:35:25,756
You know?

445
00:35:25,960 --> 00:35:27,678
So I can help you.

446
00:35:28,720 --> 00:35:29,675
I don't know.

447
00:35:29,920 --> 00:35:31,114
I do.

448
00:35:32,480 --> 00:35:33,833
I do know.

449
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:36,911
Honey, don't panic.

450
00:35:53,040 --> 00:35:55,031
Good night, Mr. Taylor.

451
00:35:55,320 --> 00:35:56,469
I'm on my way.

452
00:35:57,080 --> 00:35:59,150
Everything's prepared for you.

453
00:36:00,680 --> 00:36:02,955
Give my best to Mrs. Taylor.

454
00:36:33,720 --> 00:36:35,870
So how was the rest of your day?

455
00:36:37,200 --> 00:36:38,872
Fairly brutal.

456
00:36:40,080 --> 00:36:41,877
I'm sorry to hear about that.

457
00:36:45,240 --> 00:36:46,912
I don't want you to go tonight.

458
00:36:49,480 --> 00:36:50,674
What's wrong?

459
00:36:52,720 --> 00:36:54,631
I'd like to talk to you.

460
00:36:57,280 --> 00:36:58,713
It's too late.

461
00:36:59,640 --> 00:37:01,790
They'll never get anybody to fill in.

462
00:37:02,960 --> 00:37:07,238
Besides, I beat them last week.
They'll want their money back.

463
00:38:44,720 --> 00:38:46,312
You scared me.

464
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:49,991
I just wanted to say goodbye.

465
00:39:00,720 --> 00:39:01,835
I'll call you later.

466
00:39:03,960 --> 00:39:07,873
I might go to Nick's for a burger.
If nobody's here, don't worry.

467
00:39:09,720 --> 00:39:12,792
I won't,
but you might want to reconsider.

468
00:39:13,040 --> 00:39:14,359
Why is that?

469
00:39:14,640 --> 00:39:16,870
I had Janice make
one of her legendary roasts.

470
00:39:17,440 --> 00:39:18,555
Really?

471
00:39:20,440 --> 00:39:21,998
Thought we'd eat before the game.

472
00:39:23,640 --> 00:39:24,868
Wish me luck.

473
00:39:25,840 --> 00:39:27,159
Good luck.

474
00:41:11,200 --> 00:41:12,633
$1,000 to you, George.

475
00:41:12,840 --> 00:41:13,909
Fold.

476
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:19,398
-Call.
-Down and dirty.

477
00:41:19,640 --> 00:41:21,312
Last one, gentlemen.

478
00:41:27,760 --> 00:41:31,230
-Got to have more than that.
-Three sixes still bets.

479
00:42:03,840 --> 00:42:07,196
-Gentlemen, same game.
-It's getting a little boring.

480
00:42:16,520 --> 00:42:17,794
I'm out.

481
00:42:37,440 --> 00:42:39,396
Must be morning in Hong Kong.

482
00:43:00,480 --> 00:43:01,549
There's my cards.

483
00:43:02,160 --> 00:43:04,196
Let's have a better hand this time.

484
00:43:40,880 --> 00:43:42,199
You've got to be kidding me.

485
00:44:09,360 --> 00:44:11,191
That's a serious bet.

486
00:44:18,880 --> 00:44:20,438
Who is this?

487
00:45:43,840 --> 00:45:45,068
I'm in.

488
00:45:45,600 --> 00:45:48,433
-Put your money up, here we go.
-Just in time!

489
00:45:48,680 --> 00:45:51,069
Different winner this time,
though, guys.

490
00:45:51,640 --> 00:45:52,834
I liked the last one.

491
00:47:21,760 --> 00:47:23,318
Oh, my God!

492
00:47:26,680 --> 00:47:29,274
-What happened?
-Mrs. Taylor, we have your location.

493
00:47:29,520 --> 00:47:31,112
He's in the kitchen.

494
00:47:31,360 --> 00:47:33,112
Please stay on the line.

495
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:35,718
Ma'am? Ma'am?

496
00:47:42,440 --> 00:47:43,634
Oh, Jesus!

497
00:48:59,640 --> 00:49:01,198
Police! Open up!

498
00:49:09,560 --> 00:49:10,788
Open up!

499
00:49:12,440 --> 00:49:13,998
-Mr. Taylor?
-We're all right.

500
00:49:14,240 --> 00:49:16,879
He's in the kitchen.
I think he's dead. Follow me.

501
00:49:29,840 --> 00:49:31,717
You didn't hear any...

502
00:49:32,320 --> 00:49:34,470
...strange sounds...

503
00:49:35,560 --> 00:49:38,154
...prior to your entering the kitchen?

504
00:49:39,360 --> 00:49:41,476
No, just the phone call.

505
00:49:41,760 --> 00:49:44,433
But before that, nothing unusual?

506
00:49:52,080 --> 00:49:55,072
-How you guys doing?
-We're pretty set here.

507
00:49:55,360 --> 00:49:57,555
I want you to dust the elevator cage...

508
00:49:58,080 --> 00:49:59,672
...and the banister.

509
00:49:59,920 --> 00:50:02,912
Mo, be out of here in 1 5, 20 minutes.

510
00:50:04,800 --> 00:50:05,869
Maybe.

511
00:50:13,040 --> 00:50:15,031
-Detective Karaman.
-Steven Taylor.

512
00:50:15,280 --> 00:50:17,396
Pleasure, sir.
Mind if I ask you a few questions?

513
00:50:17,680 --> 00:50:18,829
No. Not at all.

514
00:50:19,480 --> 00:50:21,596
I noticed what I assume
to be your footprints...

515
00:50:21,840 --> 00:50:23,990
...in the blood around the deceased.

516
00:50:24,760 --> 00:50:26,716
-Can I assume those are yours?
-Yes, you may.

517
00:50:26,960 --> 00:50:28,313
May I ask what you were doing?

518
00:50:29,760 --> 00:50:31,352
Making sure he was dead.

519
00:50:32,920 --> 00:50:33,636
Was he?

520
00:50:33,920 --> 00:50:35,558
Appeared to be, yes.

521
00:50:35,920 --> 00:50:36,875
Take his pulse?

522
00:50:37,960 --> 00:50:38,756
No.

523
00:50:40,240 --> 00:50:41,150
You see right there?

524
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:44,797
Did you lean over him for something?

525
00:50:45,040 --> 00:50:47,395
I tried to determine whether
he was breathing.

526
00:50:48,680 --> 00:50:51,114
-Was he?
-Not at that time.

527
00:50:51,360 --> 00:50:52,509
Let's take a look.

528
00:51:15,400 --> 00:51:16,674
